{"id"=>194, "name"=>"Sylvia's Place - Metropolitan Community Church of New York", "category"=>"Shelters and Transitional Housing", "website"=>"http://mccny.org/", "notes"=>"MCCNY provides social services through MCCNY Charities, a comprehensive social service provider, working within and beyond the LGBTQI community. An independent 501(c)(3) organization, MCCNY Charities furthers the mission of MCCNY to bring the world to right and just relationship. MCCNY Charities operates MCCNY Homeless Youth Services: Sylviaâ€™s Place, a provider of emergency shelter and services to over 1,000 homeless LGBTQ youth per year, the Sylvia Rivera Food Pantry providing 550 bag lunches and 250 bags of groceries per week to those in need in the community, Rev. Patâ€™s Finishing School, A monthly free dinner and skills-building workshop for members of the transgender community and Queer Elder Spirit which offers training and job placement for members of the LGBTQI community to serve as home care and personal care attendants to LGBTQI elders.", "phone"=>"718-300-0133\r\nLeave a message to attainment more information", "address"=>"Metro Community Church\r\n446 West 36th Street\r\nNew York, NY 10018", "contact"=>"", "referral"=>"", "eligibility"=>"Clients must identify as LGBT (male and female) and be 16 to 23 years old", "insurance"=>"", "created_at"=>DateTime.parse('Fri, 27 Feb 2015 22:01:14 UTC +00:00'), "updated_at"=>DateTime.parse('Fri, 27 Feb 2015 22:03:52 UTC +00:00')},
{"id"=>195, "name"=>"Good Shepherd Services", "category"=>"Shelters and Transitional Housing", "website"=>"http://www.goodshepherds.org/programs.html", "notes"=>"Good Shepherd Services operates more than 80 programs in high-need communities throughout New York City united by a common goal: to help vulnerable youth and families find a safe passage to self-sufficiency.  Youâ€™ll find us where weâ€™re needed most â€“ in communities stressed by poverty and crime, in failing schools, or working to address the needs of young people who cannot live with their families.  Though our programs and services are diverse, our approach is always the same.  We surround youth and families with the right services, at the right time, for long enough to make a difference.  This wraparound approach helps young people to build a wide range of skills and build strong connections with caring adults, peers, and the broader community.  LGBTQ-friendly.\r\n\r\nBronx: Broad range of community, family, and school-based services; foster boarding home and adoption services; group homes for boys and girls.\r\n\r\nBrooklyn: Broad range of community, family, and school-based services.\r\n\r\nManhattan: Broad range of residential programs for adolescents, supportive/transitional housing for young adults, school-based support services, job readiness training, and professional training services.", "phone"=>"Phone: 212-243-7070\r\nTTY: 800-376-0219\r\nFax: 212-929-3412\r\n", "address"=>"", "contact"=>"", "referral"=>"", "eligibility"=>"Must be 18 to 22-years-old", "insurance"=>"", "created_at"=>DateTime.parse('Fri, 27 Feb 2015 22:09:50 UTC +00:00'), "updated_at"=>DateTime.parse('Fri, 27 Feb 2015 22:09:50 UTC +00:00')},
{"id"=>196, "name"=>"Institute for Contemporary Psychotherapy", "category"=>"Mental Health/Behavioral Health Programs", "website"=>"http://icpnyc.org/", "notes"=>"PCGS provides affirmative, supportive psychotherapy to the LGBTQ community and recognizes the range and diversity of gender and sexuality within all of us. We will develop a personal treatment plan for you and choose an appropriate therapist. During the initial interview, your intake counselor will discuss the selection of a therapist, the frequency of sessions, and fees. Our fees are based on a sliding scale. Your treatment begins within two weeks after your initial phone call. Your call is strictly confidential.", "phone"=>"Phone: 212-333-3444 to schedule an intake appointment\r\nFax: 212-333-5444", "address"=>"1841 Broadway (at 60th Street)\r\n4th Floor\r\nNew York, NY 10023", "contact"=>"", "referral"=>"", "eligibility"=>"", "insurance"=>"ICP accepts HIP, Medicare, 1199, and Chickering health insurances. If your Chickering insurance is through Columbia University, you must first obtain a referral.\r\n\r\nFor patients without insurance, or with insurance that we do not accept, PCGS and ICP offer fees on a sliding scale. The initial intake appointment is a $60 flat fee. After that session, our intake committee will review the income-verification documents you provide to create a fair fee. Lower-income individuals or full-time students pay on the lower end of the scale, while higher-income individuals pay more. The intake fee falls at about the middle of our scale.", "created_at"=>DateTime.parse('Mon, 02 Mar 2015 15:00:56 UTC +00:00'), "updated_at"=>DateTime.parse('Mon, 02 Mar 2015 15:03:57 UTC +00:00')},
{"id"=>123, "name"=>"Safe Horizon â€“ Streetwork Overnight", "category"=>"Shelters and Transitional Housing", "website"=>"http://www.safehorizon.org/streetwork", "notes"=>"Everyone needs to go through community intake.\r\nReferral documents need to be filled out and emailed to the supervisors (see Contacts).\r\nPlease make sure that all supervisors are included in the email you send. Please find the fax number to our site in the signature if you prefer to send the documents via fax. Once the form has been received and reviewed a decision will be made, if there is an available bed, at 3:30pm.\r\n\r\nBronx location for DV counseling: 1130 Grand Concourse\r\n", "phone"=>"Community intake: 855-234-1042, (P)917-507-1562 (F)917-507-5870", "address"=>"", "contact"=>"Shawana McIntyre (Director): Shawana.McIntyre@safehorizon.org   Giorgio Handman: Giorgio.Handman@safehorizon.org   Ieshea Green: Ieshea.Green@safehorizon.org", "referral"=>"Call Community Intake from 9-4pm. ", "eligibility"=>"", "insurance"=>"", "created_at"=>DateTime.parse('Wed, 07 Jan 2015 17:51:13 UTC +00:00'), "updated_at"=>DateTime.parse('Mon, 02 Mar 2015 15:08:55 UTC +00:00')},
{"id"=>197, "name"=>"Xmental: Mentoring Using the Power of Art", "category"=>"Youth Programs", "website"=>"http://www.xmental.org/", "notes"=>"An 8 week mentoring program that works primarily with justice involved/\"under-served\" youth. The first few classes teach the history of street art and graffiti, then move into hip hop culture, how street art can affect the community in positive ways. Teaches self confidence and self realization through knowledge of hip hop/street art history and culture. The coordinator also teaches classes in family court in the Bronx every Thursday from 4-6.", "phone"=>"Ralph's contact: 347-295-0796", "address"=>"", "contact"=>"Ralph Perez, former BxD attorney.", "referral"=>"If you have a referral, email info to this address: info@xmental.org and they'll get in touch with us/client", "eligibility"=>"", "insurance"=>"", "created_at"=>DateTime.parse('Mon, 02 Mar 2015 15:05:00 UTC +00:00'), "updated_at"=>DateTime.parse('Mon, 02 Mar 2015 15:11:33 UTC +00:00')},
